title: For Sale:  *WTS - SOLD SOLD PRICED FOR QUICK SALE - Over / Under 12ga
postcontent:
SOLS SOLD SOLD

For sale, Olin Kodensha Nikko E-712 (Winchester 101) competitively priced for a quick sale. Sale of this shotgun will fund another project.

Nikko E-712, 28" Solid Rib, 12ga Over and Under. Fixed chokes(full/mod). Hand engraved/ Hand checkered. This model is rarer than the standard EVB-712. This gun was made on the exact same tooling as ALL Winchester model 101's. The only difference is this gun has hand selected, first pick stocks(wood) and a nickel coated receiver(as opposed to blued like 101's. This gun is manufactured and assembled by the same people contracted to manufacture 101's. It uses the same parts.

Condition: This firearm is considered "good" condition, and was recently purchased from On Target Guns of Kalamazoo, hand picked and recommended by the owner(Eric) as one of the best over and unders on the shelves @ that price point ($800-$1200USD) IMO its metal is 75-80%, wood is 85-90%, bore is 90-95% and very shiny. The gun has a natural patina visible in artificial light. In daylight the bluing looks great. There are some  blemishes as expected in an older gun and are only cosmetic and do not effect function in any way. I have added 10 ounces of shot in a custom configuration that noticeably reduces felt recoil by 20-40%. The added weight is removable and placed in the butt stock bolt hole, behind the factory butt plate. Butt stock cast right for right hand shooters. It shoulders very naturally for a med-large person. I weigh 165ish, and my brother weighs 220ish, and we both agree that it is very comfortable to operate.

This gun shoots better than my 2000 dollar Beretta O/U. It was assembled by Japanese for Japanese. It was not meant for westerner devils and was treated with more care and
respect because of this. That's one reason for the nickel plating and hand selected first pick french hardwood blanks.

This gun performs awesome! It locks up tight and performs extremely accurately. It breaks tight, and not at all loose or sloppy. It features auto ejectors and boy do they kick out those empties with a positive "click"! The box type lock lever is visually cast to the right of center indicating very minimal usage. As over and unders wear, the lever will slowly drift leftward indicating heavy usage. That is NOT the case here.

This gun is my first choice field gun and I have walked with it during the 2013-2014 upland game season. It has more belt "notches" than my Italian O/U. It swings great and handles perfect. Tang mounted, selectable trigger with integrated safety. The only thing I have done mechanically is remove the stock and action covers, clean years of dust and garbage out, in kerosene parts washer, and greased with white lithium grease, and resealed.

I have found another interest which, to me, outweighs these features. Therefor it must go to appease the wife. Pfft! -'Grumbles "happy wife, happy bla bla bla" under breath'.

What does all of this mean to you?

It means you get a great gun at a great price. First 700 takes it! This is a firm, fair price and not priced high to make you feel like you got a great deal because you talked me down to 700. I have many gun sales under my belt and I know this will be a quick one.

Because of serious requests to reduce price, PRICE REDUCED TO 600 OBO! One time reduction.

Good luck, and Thanks for looking! Next owner will not be dissatisfied!

I will sale $425 firm or $475 OBO lol 
Can meet close to greensboro 30mins maybe

Yugo SKS

The SKS series created by a soviet named Sergei Gavrilovich Simonov is truly a success in the firearm industry. Why? Looking at the variety of SKS released today, why won’t it be a success? China’s success in the marketing of SKS series is the biggest example that Sergei’s masterpiece was truly influential to several countries. Russia, East Germany, Romania, North Korea, Albania, China etc. had their own variations of the SKS series. But what would be the best in quality? The Yugo SKS would be the best among the rest.

Yugo SKS with Grenade Launcher

Today, the most popular SKS rifles are the ones made by Yugoslavia particularly the Yugoslavian Model 59/66. Updated versions of this model had a 22 mm grenade launcher attached to it which is a very good addition to boost up the firepower and capabilities of the Yugoslavian Model 59/66. In combination with the 22 mm grenade launcher is a Front Sight with a fold-up ladder for a better grenade shooting accuracy. Because of the addition of the grenade launcher, manufacturers of the Yugoslavian Model 59/66 made adjustments for safety precautions of the users. When the grenade launcher sight is lifted up, the gas system is blocked for safety and the action of the gun must be manually cycled up to get back to its original status. Another means for safety precaution is that the grenade launcher can only be fired if the cartridge is empty. The stock is made up of Beech wood which is actually a fine piece of wood.

The first releases of the Yugoslavian SKS models were high-quality and still lives up to the reputation today. Newly released models actually had a very considerable price and if not taken as soon as possible, prices may climb to enormous heights and make the model expensive enough to consider. So it is advisable for firearm collectors to hastily purchase one because the demand for the Yugo SKS is actually high. It isn’t really a surprise because the Yugoslavian variants lived up to the reputation they made. They created variants that are very good in quality. They are highly durable, has high accuracy, incredible add-ons, incredible design, probably exceptional in all aspects. For collectors, the Yugoslavian SKS is a must have.
